Not him, but I don't think you understand that he is writing a "BHA" story that has been quite popular among writers in which they share a very loos canon of the existence of two worlds. The human one and the anthro one. The trope is that the human gets. isekai'd into the anthro one and may or may not loose his memory. This happens so much that the humans isekai'd into the anthro world created an organization called the BHA, to help humans recover from being violently isekai'd and rehabilitate into the anthro world. It may seem like a lot of effort and complication to put in, but it serves the important purpose of allowing a writer to much easier write the human protag, since they can establish that he would have the same background more or less as us: Human world with no anthros. It also makes it a lot easier for the reader to relate to them. Finally, it allows a quick template to use, to more quickly and efficiently start stories off.

(countiued)

Also, good criticism for first time writers or most writers in general is light ones. Meaning that you as the one giving the critique should never yourself suggest "heavy rework". The point of criticism is to make the writer question the reasoning, quality, and goals of their stories, so they can better decide what to do next in order to both progress in their story and writing skills. You shouldn't need to tell him to rework his story, he should decide that on his own after taking in ALL the feedback he has gotten.

>cohesive tone
>It isn't really clear
>tone is everywhere.

These statements on their own may not be erroneous, but using them as reasons why the author should do rework is a bit disingenuous. The writer already has this abstract story/idea that he wants to convey to the reader and uses the written languages to describe these thoughts to the reader. The reader can only try to interpret what the writer is trying to convey not dictate it. What you interpret as just a discombobulated tone may actually be a tone that is just off from what the writer is trying to convey and he may only need to twerk certain things. Thus total rework is counter-productive. Writing is a sum of its parts, and the even the slightest literary things can change the whole mood, tone, etc. So, Little changers and let the author decide what he want's to do with it on his own, for that is the one person he will be spending time with the most, and he needs to trust that person or he will get burned out.

Remember "Done is better than Perfect"

>He felt a light patting on his shoulder before turning to see [Name], focusing on her thin, black lips. "Hey," she whispered, holding her thumb up, over her shoulder. "I'm gonna go take a piss, I'll be back in a minute."
